They were most often encountered on the Prime Material, hiding themselves as boulders unless someone invaded their territories (though they typically allied themselves with other defenders of nature, such as treants or pech). They spent their days endlessly tending to their boulders, much like a gardener might tend to their plants. They were often called upon by druids to protect groves and other places sacred to nature, and used their innate camouflage abilities to remain staunch in their sentinel duty, sitting still for years at a time.

Name: Garcia Hotspur
Summary: Garcia Hotspur is the main protagonist of Shadows of the Damned.

Name: Gargoyle (Dungeons and Dragons)
Summary: Gargoyles are monstrosities of stone hailing from the planes of Earth. These prideful predators wait in dormancy, patiently watching for enemies to inflict pain upon. A gathering of Gargoyles oftentimes will resort to banter and bragging to pass the time.

Name: GAU-8 Avenger
Summary: The General Electric GAU-8/A Avenger is a 30mm hydraulically driven seven-barrel Gatling-type rotary autocannon that is typically mounted in the United States Air Force's Fairchild Republic A-10 Thunderbolt II. Designed specifically for the anti-tank role, the Avenger delivers very powerful rounds at a high rate of fire. The GAU-8/A is also used in the Goalkeeper CIWS ship weapon system, an autonomous and completely automatic weapon system for short-range defense of ships against highly maneuverable missiles, aircraft and fast maneuvering surface vessels

Name: Gelatinous Cube
Summary: Gelatinous Cubes are large, transparent cubes known for picking up whatever they come across. They are notoriously hard to see, with the only hints of their presence being the glint of something reflecting off of their vacuous hide or, if one was lucky, the telltale sign of floating remnants of the cube's last meal still seen dangling, inanimate, within it.

Name: Ghost (Marvel Cinematic Universe)
Summary: Ava Starr was the daughter of Elihas and Catherine Starr until they were both killed in an accidental quantum explosion. However, Ava was only left with the power to turn invisible and intangible, powers that led S.H.I.E.L.D. to recruit her as a special agent for dealing with extra-dangerous threats until she was adopted by Bill Foster. The two worked together to steal from Bill's nemesis, Hank Pym, and possibly find a solution to Ava's unstable body condition, with her working as "Ghost".

Name: Ghoul (Dungeons and Dragons)
Key: '''Ghoul''' | '''Lacedon''' | '''Elder Ghoul''' | '''Vapour Ghoul''' | '''Shadow Ghoul''' | '''Noble/Wizard Ghoul''' | '''Cleric Ghoul''' | '''Abyssal Ghoul''' | '''Flesh Seeker''' | '''Whisperer Ghoul''' | '''Gatherer Ghoul''' | '''Ghoul Warrior''' | '''Ghoul Stalker''' | '''Gravetouched Ghoul''' | '''Ghast''' | '''Darkpach Ghoul'''
Summary: Ghouls are malicious undead that haunt battlefields and scenes of slaughter. Not unlike maggots or Carrion Crawlers, they sweep to the scent of freshly killed flesh in droves to devour and consume. The first ghoul was made when Doresain, an elf worshiper of Orcus, consumed human flesh. As a reward, Orcus granted him a domain in his layer of the Abyss- however, this was lost when Yeenoghu overthrew Doresain. When Orcus failed to act on his behalf, Doresain turned back to the elf gods, who saved him from total annihilation once more.

Name: Giant Badger
Summary: Like its smaller variant, the Giant Badger is a vicious hunter and fighter, who flies into a frenzy whenever it gets hurt. They are unable to burrow in stone, but can in soil and anything softer, with the act leaving behind a 5 feet wide tunnel behind.

Name: Giant Bat (Dungeons and Dragons)
Summary: One of the many giant versions of mundane animals, the Dire Bat true to its name is a giant version of a bat. Its own body is the size of a horse, while its wing span reaches up to 15 feet long.

Name: Giant Cockroach
Summary: Far bigger and more aggressive then their regular counterparts, Giant Cockroaches are found mainly underground in areas where there's water and enough decaying organic matter, although it should be noted that they could live anywhere they wanted. In combat this creatures use chemicals they emit to cause nasua in their opponet, said chemicals also the exsoskeleton appear shiny or oily.

Name: Giant Constrictor Snake
Summary: A massive beast, the Giant Constrictor Snake is a large variant of a constrictor snake. They live in warm forests, dropping on prey from tree tops to strangle them to death.

Name: Giant Crocodile
Summary: The Giant Crocodile is a giant variant of the common crocodile and they can reach an impressive size of 30 feet.

Name: Giant Eagle
Summary: A noble creature which has its own language, the Giant Eagle is a giant version of an eagle which can be trained to be a mount.

Name: Giant Frog (Dungeons and Dragons)
Summary: A variation of the average frog, this creature can reach a size between 4-6 feet with its tongue being 3 times its body lengths. The Giant Frog will mostly hunt large insects and small animals but is known to sometimes swallow small humans too, they also are scared of fire.

Name: Giant Owl
Summary: A fearsome predator, a Giant Owl inspires fear in people due to its ability to strike its prey out of nowhere thanks to its excellent stealth abilities.

Name: Giant Shark
Summary: A massive predator, the Giant Shark roams the seas, hunting whatever crosses its path be it whales or ships. This creature is not the same as a Megalodon, as it only reaches around half of their size.

Name: Giant Stag Beetle
Summary: The Giant Stag Beetle is as the name implies, a giant version of a stag beetle. It is able to reach to a size of 10 feet long, with a horn being 8 feet long itself. Their wings are too heavy for flight but their armor makes them well defended.

Name: Giant Vulture
Summary: A giant version of the regular vulture, the Giant Vulture or also known as the Dire Vulture, is a far more aggressive creature which attacks wounded creatures in order to hasten their death.

Name: Giant Wasp (Dungeons and Dragons)
Summary: While not as exotic as other monsters in D&D a giant wasp is none the less a fearsome opponent to fight it combat due to its ability to inject one with devastating poison which can paralysis them, outside this the wasps behave like regular wasps with the only difference being what prey they hunt.

Name: Giant Weasel
Summary: The Giant Weasel is a ten feet long animal. They use their powerful jaws to attach to prey in order to suck out all their blood.

Name: Giant-Killer
Summary: Experts in fighting Giants, the Giant-Killer is a prestige class dedicated to combating that category of monsters. Often born from disasters caused by Giants, when not out hunting Giants they are often a nuisances, with them usually being boastful and arrogant. However once a Giant is involved they are the people one wants the most in the forefront.

Name: Giff
Summary: One of the many space faring races, the Giff is in appearance basically a hippopotamus walking on two legs. Their original world lost to the sands of time, the Giff can be found anywhere in space offering their services to the highest bidder. Giff are natural masters of guns, and are often trained in using a multitude of other weapons as well. They enjoy the thrill of combat, especially the sight of explosions, which is why they take payment in the form of gunpowder.

Name: Gildiss the Red Dragon
Summary: Gildiss the Red Dragon is the main antagonist of King of Dragons, a hack'n'slash game with fantasy themes.

Name: Gimli
Summary: Gimli is a stubborn, war-hungry dwarf and one of the many heroes in J.R.R Tolkien's The Lord of the Rings and Peter Jackson's films of the same name respectively. He joins the fellowship to destroy the ring and kill many orcs along the way. He is close friends with Aragorn and Legolas but still clashes with the elf due to the thousand-year-old feud between elves and dwarves. He participates in many battles including Moria, Helm's Deep and the Black Gate. His weapons include twin hatchets and a giant battle ax. He is very stubborn and often explains the stubbornness of dwarves. He loves fighting and even when outnumbered, he never backs down and always competes with Legolas to kill more orcs than him.

Name: Girallon
Summary: Girallon are a species of gorilla-like monsters found in D&D. They are known for their carniverous eating habits and their quasi-society found in the jungles of the world. Despite their animalistic intelligence, these creatures did indeed acknowledge the eldest among them as their leaders.

Name: Githyanki
Summary: Githyanki are the half of the Gith species that ended up following the original Gith, a member of their formerly nameless species hailing from a distant planet. When the time came to rebel against those who had enslaved them- the Mind Flayer empire, at the peak of its power- Gith led the charge and the Githyanki by her side. Now, battalions of the Githyanki scour the universe for more signs of their eternal foes, the Mind Flayers.

Name: Githzerai
Summary: In times long lost to the rampages of war, the Githzerai were once normal Githyanki who dissented from their brethren and formed a non-evil neutral faction. The Githzerai are ascetic monk-like folk who have settled in Limbo, a plane of chaos- a direct counter to their Lawful nature. They seek to battle the Slaadi, specifically to expand their knowledge in the face of direct adversity, building on the traits they learned from their slavery under the Mind Flayer empire.

Name: Glabbagool
Summary: An average Gelatinous Cube, Glabbagool gained heightened intelligence when the demon lord Juiblex arrived to the Underdark. Curious about the world and those in it he will not go out of his way to attack other beings but merely will self defend, he can be found in the Ooze Temple and is willing to offer assistance to adventurers who get into there, and if the part gains his trust he may even offer loot that's inside his body.

Name: Glyptodon (Dungeons And Dragons)
Summary: A prehistoric mammal, the Glyptodon lived in the Ice Age and used its mace like tail to defend itself from predators such sabertoothed tigers, dire lions, and other deadly hunters such as dragons and humans.

Name: Gnoll (Dungeons and Dragons)
Summary: It is His blessing.

Name: Goblin (Dungeons and Dragons)
Summary: They breed fast, they spread fast; the Goblins are a small humanoid race and most well known of the Goblinoids.

Name: Gordon Freeman
Summary: Dr. Gordon Freeman is the main protagonist of the Half-Life series. He is a theoretical physicist who is forced to defend himself and the Human race against hostile Aliens and other enemies following an experiment gone wrong. In the process, he becomes an almost legendary resistance hero, eventually becoming one of the leaders of an uprising against the alien invaders.

Name: Gorgon (Dungeons and Dragons)
Summary: Gorgons are horrific bull-like creatures covered head-to-toe in iron plates protecting its true body. Their plates perpetually remain oiled thanks to secretions from their skin beneath, ensuring that it never rusts and remains as silent as possible. Gorgons, when they find prey, charge through them, oftentimes simply pulverizing weaker foes. The vapors that emit from the Gorgon are known to petrify enemies on contact, and not even those on other planes can escape its effects.

Name: Gorthok, the Thunder Boar
Summary: Gorthok, the Thunder Boar is a primordial spirit taken the physical form of a monstrous boar.

Name: Gragas
Summary: Equal parts jolly and imposing, Gragas is a massive, rowdy brewmaster on his own quest for the perfect pint of ale. Hailing from parts unknown, he now searches for rare ingredients among the unblemished wastes of the Freljord, trying each recipe as he goes. Often intoxicated and extremely impulsive, he is legendary for the brawls he starts, which often end in all-night parties and widespread property damage. Any appearance from Gragas must surely foreshadow drinking and destruction—in that order.

Name: Grand Admiral Thrawn
Summary: Tier: 9-A physically. 9-A with blasters

Name: Gravik (Marvel Cinematic Universe)
Summary: Gravik was the leader of the radical Skrull Resistance and Skrull General in the Skrull Council, who grew disillusioned and spiteful of Nick Fury for abandoning him after Fury went into exile. Replacing Talos as the newly appointed Skrull General, Gravik initiated the Secret Invasion, launching covert terrorist attacks and attempting to manipulate humanity to engage in self-destructive nuclear war. By selling his movement as a way to allow the Skrulls to inhabit Earth as their new home planet, he began a war with the ultimate goal of getting revenge on Nick Fury for hurting him as a boy. Intending to raise an army of Super Skrulls, he sought the Harvest containing combatants' DNA from the Battle of Earth, although Gravik was killed by G'iah before he could fulfill his war.

Name: Green Arrow (Post-Crisis)
Summary: This page contains or depicts disturbing and/or graphic content that some may find upsetting, and that is only intended for mature audiences. Please proceed with caution.

Name: Green Hag
Summary: Green Hags are corrupted fey beings, evil incarnate originating from the land of fairies. Hags are best known for their tendencies of kidnapping and devouring children. In this way, they may birth their own kin- a week after consumption, hags birth a daughter exactly identical to their devoured counterpart, only to transform into a hag over a decade later. Hags view themselves as infinitely cunning and devious spellcasters, and will often accept dealing with mortals so long as they treat the hag with "proper" respect.

Name: Grell
Summary: Grell are creatures that resemble floating brains with tentacles and a large beak protruding from the front. They are most famous for their voracious feeding habits- they bear little else in terms of dastardly plans outside of planning their next meal, going so far as to classify all things in life as "edible", "inedible", or "Great Eater" (those few things that might feed on a grell). While generally solitary, a rare few grell form great colonies led by philosophers, grell wizards that study the aberrant sciences of their native realm. The grell are non-hostile to other grell, and generally consider the choice of joining a colony as a matter of opinion.

Name: Grick
Summary: Gricks are rubbery predators most commonly encountered in the Underdark. Generally, these creatures are passive hunters- that is to say, they create dens by populated areas and regularly traveled passes, and grab whatever passes by. They will only leave once the area becomes less populated, then searching for greener pastures. Gricks often travel in packs, led by the strongest, best fed member.

Name: Griffon (Dungeons and Dragons)
Summary: Griffons are intelligent hybrids of lions and eagles. Their majesty is often hailed by cultures throughout the planes as a sign of goodness, and as such they are regularly used as mounts for good-aligned societies. The city of Waterdeep, the largest city of Faerun, maintained a large arsenal of Griffon cavalry. Netheril and Thay are two other superpowers that wielded the might of Griffons as their cavalry units. They are known to feed almost exclusively on horse flesh.

Name: Grimlock (Dungeons and Dragons)
Summary: Grimlocks are a species of humanoid creatures descended from two tribes of ancient barbarians that disappeared into the Underdark many millennia ago. Their children, blind and decrepit, now wander in the endless vistas of darkness in the subterranean landscape, serving mightier creatures when they can.

Name: Guzma
Key: '''By Himself''' | '''Pokémon Team (Malie Garden)''' | '''Pokémon Team (Shady House)''' | '''Pokémon Team (Aether Paradise)''' | '''Pokémon Team (Hau'oli City, Team Rocket's Castle and Title Defense)'''
Summary: Guzma (Japanese: グズマ Guzma) is the leader of Team Skull.

Name: Gwenpool
Summary: Gwendolyn Poole was just a normal girl, living an unsatisfactory life and with a fierce passion for Marvel Comics, when one day she was mysterious transported within the exciting world of her beloved stories. Extremely galvanized at this prospect, Gwen donned a costume and took on the identity of Gwenpool, determined to have the most fun of her new life. Extremely erratic, reckless and borderline psychotic, Gwen viewed herself as the protagonist of the story and the world around her as a playground, uncaring for even the lives of others, for they were expendable fictional characters. However, things quickly escalated and slipped out of her hands, making her bitterly realize the harsh truth: she was not in control .

Name: Gyarados
Summary: Gyarados is a Water/Flying Pokémon introduced in Generation I. It is the evolved form of Magikarp. Extremely vicious, enormously destructive, ferociously violent, and horribly brutal, it has a very aggressive nature. Although rarely seen in the wild, once it appears it goes on a rampage. When this happens, it doesn't calm until it has burned everything down and razed the fields and mountains around it. Not even harsh storms are able to stop its rage, and there are records of this Pokémon's rampages lasting a whole month. A single Gyarados has enough destructive power to totally annihilate even a major city. Gyarados is attracted to violence and tends to appear when there is a world conflict or war. When humans begin to fight, it will appear and burn everything to the ground with intensely hot flames. During past wars Gyarados would appear and leave blazing ruins in its wake, and in ancient literature there is a record of a Gyarados that razed a village when violence flared. When Magikarp evolves into Gyarados, its brain cells undergo a structural transformation. It is said that this transformation is to blame for this Pokémon's wildly violent nature.

Name: Halfling (Dungeons and Dragons)
Summary: The closest demihuman to humans, to the point where their name comes from being half as tall as human, Halflings are a naturally lucky race. Their society values comfort and security above all else, with them seldom venturing outside their home lands besides the dire of situations. This makes any Halfling adventurer the more fierce when going out to help their local community, with Halflings being naturally gifted in ranged combat and stealth.

Name: Hammer Drones
Summary: The Hammer Drones were the result of Justin Hammer enlisting Ivan Vanko to render Iron Man obsolete. Hammer wanted manned suits, but Vanko created remote-controlled drones instead, wishing to use them to attack Tony Stark. Hammer brought the drones to the Stark Expo in the hopes of regaining his contract with the government. Vanko sabotaged Hammer's efforts by activating the drones and making them wreak havok across the site of the Expo. Iron Man and War Machine were eventually able to defeat the drones, as well as Vanko himself.

Name: Hank Pym (Marvel Cinematic Universe: What If...?)
Summary: Hank Pym, also known as Yellowjacket, is the main antagonist of "What If... the World Lost Its Mightiest Heroes?", the third episode of the Marvel animated anthology series What If...?. He is the inventor of size-changing "Pym Particles" and a former superhero working for S.H.I.E.L.D. as Ant-Man. However, after the death of his wife and daughter, he became disgruntled against Nick Fury, and decided to take revenge on him by killing every potential member for his "Avengers Initiative".
ID: Hank Pym (Marvel Cinematic Universe: What If...?)-MarvelCinematicUniverse-9-A

Name: Hanno Minstrelsong
Summary: Hanno Minstrelsong was a former thief and current businessman residing within Cormyr during the late 14th century. A proprietor of herbs and spices, Hanno generally err'd on the side of good, though he did sell non-lethal poison to those who seemed trustworthy. His original name is unknown, as he dropped it after a long, successful career as a thief- so successful than multitudes of assassins were sent to kill him, forcing him to leave his former life and adopt his position in Cormyr. He is described as always smiling.

Name: Harley Quinn (Post-Crisis)
Summary: Harley Quinn (Dr. Harleen Frances Quinzel) is a fictional character appearing in American comic books published by DC Comics, commonly as an adversary of the superhero Batman. The character was created by Paul Dini and Bruce Timm, and first appeared on Batman: The Animated Series in September 1992. She later appeared in DC Comics' Batman comic books, with her first comic book appearance in The Batman Adventures #12 (Sept. 1993).

Name: Harpy (Dungeons and Dragons)
Summary: Harpies are predatory humanoids, a grotesque mixture of vulture and human. Their origin lies in the longing of the elves- once, an elf heard the song of a beautiful bird, and as she wandered through the forest, she saw yet another elven youth- a god, unbeknownst to her. Immediately, the god fled, but the youth was struck by his presence, and came to despair when she failed to find him. Another god came to her aid, and taught her the song of the birds in an attempt to lure the other deity back. After failing, the elf maiden cursed the gods, and became the first Harpy.

Name: Hawkeye (Marvel Cinematic Universe)
Summary: Iron Man: Clearly retirement doesn't suit you. Got tired of shooting golf? Hawkeye: Well, I played 18, shot 18... Just can't seem to miss.

Name: Hellhound (Dungeons and Dragons)
Summary: Hell Hounds are a breed of extraplanar, fiery hound, often used as pets of infernal lords. Wild packs of Hell Hounds often roamed Baator, the Abyss, and even the Elemental Plane of Fire. As such, they could be found in the service of all manner of fiery outsiders, including Efreeti, Balors, and Pit Fiends.

Name: Hellwasp
Summary: Hellwasps, were insect-like fiends that inhabited the warmer levels of the Nine Hells.

Name: Helmut Zemo (Marvel Cinematic Universe)
Summary: Colonel Helmut Zemo was a member of a death squad in Sokovian Armed Forces who lost his family to Ultron during the Battle of Sokovia. Zemo blamed the Avengers and sought revenge on them. He knew the Avengers could not be beaten through force, and instead attempted to manipulate them into destroying each other and took advantage of the friction between the Avengers during the signing of the Sokovia Accords by committing acts of terrorism and framing James Barnes, causing further conflict between Steve Rogers and Tony Stark. Zemo would eventually be caught by the Black Panther and imprisoned.

Name: Hetfish
Summary: The Hetfish is a type of fish which is unable to breath in water and instead relies on their body heat to boil water around them in order to create a steam environment in which they can live in. This fish is often murdered by civilised species due to them causing damage structures.

Name: Hill Giant
Key: '''Regular''' | '''Mouth of Grolantor''' | '''Barrowghast''' | '''Maw of Yeenoghu''' | '''Wereboar''' | '''Avalancher''' | '''Scion of Grolantor'''
Summary: Hill Giants are the lowest ranked of the True Giants, and fittingly are both the dumbest and shortest of them, but they're capable of surprisingly cunning actions in combat and they still possess great physical abilities.

Name: Hinome Hawakata
Summary: Hinome is the secondary main protagonist of the Im: Great Priest Imhotep series. She's Imhotep's first friend after being set free from his punishment for 3,000 years. She's a rather unorthodox high school girl who had a dark past involving the Magai which ties into Imhotep's origins. However, she has a brave, kind, and fierce heart. Helping Imhotep in his endeavors despite being a mere human. Always being willing to stick by his side and cheering him on, making him better himself.

Name: Hippogriff (Dungeons and Dragons)
Summary: Hippogriffs are believed to be distant cousins of Griffons, though instead of being an eagle-and-lion mixture, Hippogriffs bear more resemblance to a horse. Despite this they are still remarkably popular as mounts and, much like their cousins, are regularly used in airborne cavalry units.

Name: Hobgoblin (Dungeon and Dragons)
Summary: They fall beneath our blades,

Name: Hook Horror
Summary: Hook Horrors are predators originating from the Underdark, and mixes traits of eagles and insects into a single malign entity. Unlike most animals, especially in the hostile caverns of the Underdark, Hook Horrors form castes of clans, maintaining familial ties all through its life- thus, it is not uncommon to encounter a large horde of Hook Horrors.

Name: Hope Summers
Summary: Hope Summers is a fictional character appearing in American comic books published by Marvel Comics. The superheroine first appeared in X-Men #205 in 2007 (Chapter five of the "X-Men: Messiah Complex" storyline). She is the first mutant born after the events of the "House of M" and "Decimation" storyline

Name: Howard the Duck (Marvel Comics)
Summary: Howard Duckson, native of a parallel universe named Duckworld, was but an ordinary individual like many others, stuck in aimless and unsatisfying life. On a fateful day, a shift in the cosmic axis caused Howard to be trasported across the multiverse and into our universe. Him and other people likewise stranded from their home worlds banded together to find the source of their problem, but Howard's adventure was cut short when he fell into a dimensional abyss, ending up in the city of Cleveland. Howard had no choice by trying to make sense of his new situation the best he could, amongst hairless apes living in a world he never made!

Name: Howler
Summary: Howlers are predatory animals originating from Pandemonium, a realm of pure chaos. Often the creatures are imported from the plane, generally to the Lower Planes, for use as war hounds and exotic pets, often rivaling the status of creatures such as the Hellhound. They are famed for their unique, mind-numbing howl, which cripples enemies for easier hunting.

Name: Hrabbaz
Summary: Hrabbaz is a half-orc bodyguard currently working for the House of Gradlhund in Watredeep. He is extremely loyal to Yalah Gralhund while finding her husband annoying and hoping he'll be knocked down a peg.

Name: Hulking Hurler
Summary: A class for massive creatures, the Hulking Hurler is someone who specializes in throwing objects incredibly hard. Often found amongst Giants, there are some smaller creatures which employ these tactics and act as a sort of artillery.

Name: Hush (Post-Crisis)
Summary: Thomas Elliot is a renowned surgeon and childhood friend of Bruce Wayne. A meticulous planner, Elliot resents the fact that Bruce's father thwarted his plot to murder his parents. Aware of Bruce Wayne's secret identity, and assuming the identity of criminal mastermind Hush, he sets out to destroy Batman.

Name: Hydra (Dungeons and Dragons)
Summary: Hydras are monstrosities with crocodile-like bodies and serpentine heads, ranging in number from five to twelve. Each hydra is descended from the primordial hydras, created when the dragon goddess Tiamat slew a fellow dragon deity, spreading her blood across the multiverse, each blood drop spawning a fearsome hydra. Hydras are famed for their unending hunger, for their sickening gluttony that often leads each head to turn on each other, devouring itself alive. Many warriors would hunt down and kill a Hydra in order to prove their strength.

Name: I, Vampire (Pre-Flashpoint)
Summary: The only vampire capable of resisting his own lust for blood, Andrew Bennett, I, Vampire, is a hunter of his own kind, having dedicated his immortal life to taking the life of Mary, Queen of Blood, his former love, and her Cult of the Blood Red Moon.

Name: Ibrandlin
Summary: Ibrandlin, also known as lurkers in Darkness is a dragon like creature which is was created by priests of Ibrandul and are trained to be guards of various places.

Name: Ice Mephit
Summary: The cruelest of Mephits, the Ice Mephit is composed of air and water. Alongside a Mephit's usual array of abilities, they have many cold-based abilities, being able to generate ice and fog alike.

Name: Imp (Dungeons and Dragons)
Summary: Imps are the most typical and average devils above the lemure fodder. Imps serve any number of purposes for their Archdevil overlords, ranging from assassins, foot-soldiers, scouts, and general cannon fodder.

Name: Intellect Devourer
Summary: Intellect Devourers are, in simple terms, transformed brains of the victims of Mind Flayers. They are intelligent predators bred to take over the bodies of others, draining their intellect, and using their hollow shell to lure in more victims. As such, the creatures are extremely dangerous monstrosities that often rake in multiple victims.

Name: Invisible Blade
Summary: Masters of daggers and similar weapons, the Invisible Blade often appears suicidal to those looking from the side. However, their prowess with the blade is such that they can slay opponents far larger than them despite carrying nothing but a blade.

Name: Invisible Stalker
Summary: Invisible Stalkers are elementals originating from the Elemental Plane of Air, and are most commonly encountered as minions of stronger spellcasters. The creatures themselves are truly made of air, and almost impossible to detect as a result. They often tear enemies apart from the inside, viciously dealing with the enemies of their masters.

Name: Iowa-class Battleship
Key: '''Pre-Refit (World War II/Korean War/Vietnam War-era)''' | '''Post-Refit (Persian Gulf War-era)'''
Summary: The Iowa-class battleships were a class of fast battleships designed and fielded by the United States Navy in 1939–1940 to escort their Fast Carrier Task Forces operating in the Pacific Theater during World War II. Four were completed, while two more were laid down but were not finished before the war's end and were ultimately scrapped. Like other third-generation American battleships, the Iowa class emphasized speed in addition to secondary and anti-aircraft batteries.

Name: Iron Fist (Marvel Cinematic Universe)
Summary: Danny Rand was the child of owners of Rand Enterprises. After a plane crash where his parents died he was rescued by two monks who took him to K'un-Lun where he trained and later earned the title of Iron Fist.

Name: Iron Man (Marvel Comics)
Key: '''Human''' | '''Extremis Enhanced and RepulsorTech Node''' | '''With Iron Man Armors''' | '''Cosmic Iron Man'''
Summary: Iron Man, or Tony Stark, is the main hero of a comic by the same name. Stark: an inventive genius, industrialist, and multi-billionaire, went to Vietnam to oversee a field test for one of his transistorized weapons, that his company Stark Industries made.

Name: Iron Man Armor Model 1
Summary: Model 1 was the first ever Iron Man armor created by Anthony Stark with help of Ho Yinsen, with the purpose of keep Stark heart beating after having his chest being lodged with shrapnel and as way to escape from his capturers in Vietnam. It would later be upgraded into several new advanced armors over the years.

Name: Iron Man Armor Model 2
Summary: After a disastrous battle with the criminal known as Mister Doll, Tony Stark came to realize that the Iron Man Armor Model 1 was too cumbersome, especially in his state, which caused specially an unnecessary excessive use of energy for the armor to simply sustain its own weight. To remedy this, Tony designed a sleeker, lightweight armor while increasing its strength.

Name: Ironheart (Marvel Cinematic Universe)
Summary: Riri Williams is an MIT student, and one of the smartest people on earth. She was hired by the CIA to find vibranium, but later got taken by the Wakandans to find the Tolokanil base. She has created a suit of armor for herself, granting her the name Ironheart.

Name: Isabeau (In Stars and Time)
Summary: Isabeau Manon Constantin Moineau is a major character in the game In Stars and Time and START AGAIN: a prologue, traveling with Mirabelle, Odile, Siffrin, and Bonnie on a quest to defeat the King and save Vaugarde from the fate of being frozen in time. Isabeau is a kind, cheerful person from the city of Jouvente. Throughout the game, he’s often shown making puns with Siffrin.

Name: Isti-Zar
Summary: Isti-Zar was a banelar naga serving the Church of Cyric, the Mad God, in the 14th century. He was allied with the followers of Shar attempting to create a magical dead zone in the Vast Marsh by tearing and ripping a hole in the Spellweave. During this time, Isti-Zar was slain by an adventuring party invading his territory, failing to assist the cult he had been allied with.

Name: Izek Stranzi
Summary: A child born with no soul, Izek Stranzi naturally lacked the emotional capacity granted by the souls of humans. He only felt emotion in regards to his family. One night, his family was attacked by a dire wolf, separating him from his sister.

Name: Jack Cooper (Titanfall 2)
Summary: As the main and playable protagonist of Titanfall 2, Rifleman Jack Cooper forms a bond with his Titan, BT-7274, in the game's campaign, where he and his new ally must complete their mission that could save multiple worlds in the frontier from destruction. He stands with the Militia against the IMS, the two strongest factions in the Frontier.

Name: Jackalwere
Summary: Jackalwere are infernal creatures created by the demon lord Graz'zt to serve his insidious servants, the Lamias. Cowards and charmers, the Jackalwere lulls enemies into a false sense of security and ease, then tears them apart. The creatures are designed to lie and to steal, to kidnap and to kill, for their masters.

Name: Jaculi
Summary: Being a 15 foot long snake it uses its innate camouflage abilities which it derives from the ability to alter its skin to either stone or wood it uses it to sneak on top of a tree and then long at an unsuspecting target with the precision and power of a spear.

Name: Jericho Swain
Summary: Tier: 9-A | 7-C

Name: Jessica Jones (Marvel Cinematic Universe)
Summary: Jessica Jones is a private investigator from New York City. After she was orphaned at a young age, Jones was taken in by Dorothy Walker and developed a sisterly bond with her daughter, Trish. During adolescence, Jones discovered she possessed superhuman strength and used her ability in adulthood to fight crime as a superhero.

Name: Jigsaw (Marvel Cinematic Universe)
Summary: William "Billy" Russo was abandoned by his mother as a child and taken in at the Ray of Hope group home, until he suffered injuries while fighting off abuse by one of the carers. Joining the U.S. Marine Corps by adulthood, he became close friends with Francis "Frank" Castle, but they were both recruited into Operation Cerberus, a secret illegal military drug trafficking scheme in Afghanistan which resulted in the murder of an Afghan police officer and the deaths of numerous soldiers, ostensibly to help win the war. After returning home, Billy (who now owned a private military firm) was hired by the operation's ringleader to cover up the campaign by killing all involved personnel still alive, including Frank (now known as "the Punisher"), but the conspiracy was ultimately foiled and Russo's face was violently mutilated during a fight with his former friend, before being arrested.

Name: John Pilgrim
Summary: A man known only as Robert was once an assassin who did work for the Aryan Brotherhood until he was imprisoned following a failed assassination at a bar. Bailed out by Anderson and Eliza Schultz, leaders of the powerful Testament Industries corporation, Robert turned to a new life as pious family man and pastor John Pilgrim.

Name: K-999
Summary: K-999 is a robotic dog created by Tux Dog to assist the Problem Solverz. He was programmed with the task of assisting the Problem Solverz with solving problems, although for the most part, he only got in their way and acted as a nuisance in his first appearance on the show. He is friendly towards Alfe and has a small disdain for Roba and Horace.

Name: Kagha
Summary: Kagha is a low-level archdruid who places herself in control of the Emerald Grove following the disappearance of the grove's master, Halsin, amidst the Absolute Crisis in 1492 DR. Kagha is secretly an agent of the Shadow Druids, a follower of Archdruid Kaelis who subtly goaded Kagha to accept her patronage, leading her to believe that the grove would be safer in their hands. As a result, when she became First Druid, Kagha worked to seal the grove from the outside world in its entirety, attempting to forcefully banish a large group of tieflings in doing so.

Name: Kamen Rider Kuuga
Key: '''Yusuke Godai''' | '''Growing Form''' | '''Regular Forms''' | '''Rising Forms''' | '''Amazing Mighty Form''' | '''Ultimate Form'''
Summary: I don't want to see people crying anymore. I want everyone to smile! So have a good look... at my... transformation!

Name: Kamen Rider OOO
Key: '''Eiji Hino''' | '''The Revival of Greeed, the Birth of OOO, and the Scramble of Medals (Episodes 1-16)''' | '''The Man of One Hundred Million, the Other Ankh, and the Purple Medals (Episodes 17-38)''' | '''The Bond of Allies, the End of the World, and the Greed Towards Tomorrow (Episodes 39-48)''' | '''Post-Series''' | '''Heisei Generations FINAL''' | '''OOO 10th: Core Medal of Resurrection'''
Summary: Eiji Hino (火野 映司, Hino Eiji?) is the main protagonist of Kamen Rider OOO. He is a 21-year-old homeless traveller who was the son of a politician. When traveling to Africa, he befriended a little girl named Ruu and attempted to use his fortune to help her struggling village. Unfortunately, this would drag Eiji into the civil war that this village was involved in. During the situation, he failed to save Ruu from being tragically killed. Eiji was then held for ransom which his parents ended up paying for, as well as using the situation as a means to gain support for their public platform.

Name: Kang the Conqueror (Marvel Cinematic Universe)
Summary: Nathaniel Richards was a scientist from the 31st Century who discovered the Multiverse's existence and joined the Council of Kangs in ruling over the foreseeable realities. Deeming the council's actions to be destroying the Multiverse, Richards sparked the Multiversal War, seeking to conquer as many worlds as possible as Kang the Conqueror. However, the council decided to banish him to the Quantum Realm, where he allied with Janet van Dyne to rebuild his Time Sphere, until he was betrayed after van Dyne discovered his true nature. Kang was once again trapped in the Quantum Realm, using that time to conquer part of it and build an empire in Axia.

Name: Karate Kid (Earth-Prime)
Summary: Val Armorr, the Karate Kid, is a founding member of the Legion of Super-Heroes, a group of teenagers inspired by the actions of superheroes from centuries ago, to rise up and stand against a society of quiet inaction and strict protocol.

Name: Katana (Post-Crisis)
Summary: Tatsu Yamashiro (or just Katana) is a samurai warrior whose skill with a sword allows her to fight for justice as a superhero. Her tragic backstory includes the death of her husband, Maseo, whose soul becomes trapped in her blade, the Soultaker.

Name: Kate Bishop (Marvel Cinematic Universe)
Summary: Clint: This life you wanna live. To really help people. I mean, try to help people, anyway. Comes a lot of sacrifices. And some things you'll lose... forever. Kate: Well, there's also things you gain, like trick arrows and a cool costume.

Name: Ketsarra Shadowscale
Summary: Ketsarra Shadowscale is one of two leaders of a cult of Shar, and is the half-dragon lizardfolk descendant of the dragon Despayr, an extremely unique dragon with strong ties to the Plane of Shadow. Ketsarra was made into an undead shadowy creature at birth as a pawn in Despayr's schemes. Ketsarra became the leader of the Dragonslayer tribe of lizardfolk (an ironic title to hold) and commanded tribes on both the Prime and the Plane of Shadow.

Name: KGBeast (Post-Crisis)
Summary: Trained by a top-secret cell of the KGB known as The Hammer, Anatoli Knyazev was an assassin known to the C.I.A. as the KGBeast. Having over 200 kills in his debut he was sent to America by The Hammer to assassinate 10 U.S officials, one of which was to visit Gotham City. This caught the Batman's eye and after battling twice the Beast cut his left arm off after it was restrained by the Batrope. He had his left arm replaced with a cybernetic gun, but in their 3rd battle Batman destroyed the gun arm and trapped him in a sewer where, he was later captured by police. Despite this, Anatoli escaped and became a recurring enemy of Batman, until he was killed by Tally Man under orders by Great White Shark.

Name: Killer Moth (Post-Crisis)
Summary: Having decided that the lawbreakers of Gotham City needed a costumed protector just as honest citizens had Batman, Drury Walker emulated the Dark Knight in every way, copying his paraphernalia and building on his legend to create his own super villain identity, The Killer Moth. He eventually came to resemble a dark mirror image of Batman, even adopting the alter ego of a wealthy philanthropist similar to Bruce Wayne. Moth was motivated by greed rather than justice, and only served the criminal underworld for a price.

Name: King of Feathers
Summary: A monstrous Tyrannosaurus Rex, the King of Feathers was a beast that served the monster lord of Omu and was feared by all creatures in the forbidden city. Its name is from the fact that it has a plumage across its head, outside this it was also different from a regular T-Rex via its magical abilities like being able to cast Misty Step and summoning swarms of wasps

Name: Kingdom of Blackmoor
Summary: An ancient nation that predates the modern world of Mystara. Possessing hyper-advanced technology, Blackmoor was able to construct weapons of enormous destruction and objects of incredible power. Prideful and arrogant, eventually they destroyed themselves when a nuclear reactor went critical and destroyed the majority of their civilization. The survivors of Blackmoor would colonize another planet, but like before their arrogance resulted in their destruction.

Name: Kingpin (Marvel Cinematic Universe)
Summary: Wilson Grant Fisk is a powerful businessman and crime lord with an interest in controlling New York City. Having formed alliances with other criminal enterprises, Fisk used the aftermath of the Battle of New York to gain power in the city, and attempting to rebuild Hell's Kitchen by destroying and gentrifying it. His criminal activities brought him into a conflict with Daredevil, as well as some of his partners who betrayed him, and he was arrested after his actions were leaked to the FBI. Within Ryker's Island, Fisk began building up a following and came to run the prison. Seeking to destroy the crime competition in New York by the time he got free, Fisk assisted with the Punisher's escape, as he desired to eliminate all competing criminal empires as the Kingpin, pitting him in conflict with Nelson and Murdock who had sought to send him to prison.

Name: Kingpin (Marvel Comics)
Summary: The Kingpin (real name Wilson Fisk) is a major fictional Marvel Comics supervillain that originated in the Spider-Man comics and media. He has since then gone on to be a major enemy of Daredevil as well as a recurring villain for both Spider-Man and the Punisher. In recent years, he has been revised as being more of Daredevil's enemy rather than Spider-Man's and has appeared in more mature, realistic and adult-themed comic appearances. He is portrayed as one of the most feared and powerful crime lords in the Marvel Universe, typically holding the position of New York City's crime overlord.

Name: Kithlord Thieraven
Summary: Kithlord Thieraven was a Shadar-Kai Sorcerer and ally of Esvele Greycastle, a cleric of Shar. Thieraven was drawn to the dark goddess when an offer of sanctuary was made- while the curse of the Shadar Kai couldn't be dealt with, its effects could be mitigated if Thieraven assisted Esvele's other contact in tearing a whole in the Spellweave. So it was that Thieraven joined Ketsarra Shadowscale in the Vast Swamp and began preparations.

Name: Kled
Summary: A warrior as fearless as he is ornery, Kled is a popular folk hero in Noxus. Embodying the furious bravado of his nation, he is an icon beloved by the empire's soldiers, distrusted by its officers, and loathed by the nobility. Tall tales such as "The Great Hussar", "The High General Marshal Sergeant", and "The Mountain Admiral" trace back to the founding of the empire. Many soldiers claim Kled has fought in every campaign the legions have waged, has "acquired" every military title, and has never once backed down from a fight. Though the veracity of the details is often questionable, one part of his legend is undeniable: Charging into battle on his untrusty steed, Skaarl, Kled fights to protect what's his...and to take whatever he can get.

Name: Knell Beetle
Summary: Being an off shoot of giant beetles they're a mutated form of giant beetles due to magic and sonic energies, being mindless hunters who only seek to breed they make great use of their innate magical abilities and deadly claws in combat.

Name: Kobold (Dungeons and Dragons)
Summary: Kobolds are the lowest evolutionary form of dragons, and worship Tiamat (and her lesser god vassal, Kurtulmak, in particular). The creatures are cowardly, conniving, and experts in teamwork. Due in large part to their physical frailty, kobolds are extremely easy prey for the larger creatures of the world. Thus, Kobolds tend to form massive warbands fitted with warriors, mages, and inventors to increase their likelihood of survival.

Name: Korath the Pursuer (Marvel Cinematic Universe)
Summary: Vers: Has a Skrull ever simmed you? Korath: Once. It was deeply disturbing. Vers: Why? Korath: Because I stared into the face of my mortal enemy and the face staring back was my own. Att-Lass: Maybe if you were more attractive, then it would be less disturbing. Korath: You think you’re funny. I’m not laughing. Att-Lass: You never laugh. Korath: I laugh, on the inside. I’m not doing it now.

Name: Kraken Priest
Summary: A Kraken Priest is a humanoid spellcaster devoted to serving a Kraken in exchange for power, with those who become priests likely having mistaken the kraken's fury as a sign of divine power, or are simply twisted enough to appraise the kraken in awe.

Name: Kree (Marvel Cinematic Universe)
Summary: Gleen Talbot: You're telling me that we got our asses handed to us by little green men. Phil Coulson: They were big and blue.

Name: Kuo-Toa
Summary: Kuo-Toa are a species of fish-human hybrids that once dominated the surface world, ruling the islands and seas alike. However, they were driven away from their homes, deep into the Underdark, the evil world beneath the world.

Name: Kureto Hiragi
Summary: Kureto Hiragi is a lieutenant general in the Imperial Demon Army and the brother of Shinoa and Mahiru. He killed his father to become the head of the Hiragi family.

Name: Lady Fiona Wachter
Summary: Lady Fiona Wachter is the leader of a cult of devil worshipers within Vallaki. She actively seeks to overcome the current Burgomaster, and seeks to manipulate any tools she might come into contact with to pursue this goal. Through illusory devil summoning and political planning, she aims to turn the town against the current Burgomaster, and place herself in charge, subservient to Strahd von Zarovich.

Name: Langdedrosa Cyanwrath
Summary: Langdedrosa Cyanwrath is a champion of the Cult of the Dragon initially introduced as an invader of the town of Greenest. He is a warrior and acts as a defender of his master- Frulam Mondath. Together the two sacked the town, destroying its supplies, capturing its members, and killing its defenders. If allowed to live, Langdedrosa goes on to defend a sanctuary of Tiamat, and is killed in combat.

Name: Lantern Archon
Summary: Lantern Archons are simple celestial beings, gaseous orbs of light and the lowest orders of the Archons defending the Celestial realms. Often they are the converted souls of the Lawful Good mortals of the Prime Material. As newly converted souls, regardless of their intelligence in life, they are often simple creatures, merely the simple embodiment of goodness and order.

Name: Leopard (Dungeons and Dragons)
Summary: One of the many animals that roam the jungle, the Leopard is a big feline that jumps down from trees in order to hunt.

Name: Leucrotta
Summary: An evil and repulsive creature, the Leucrotta enjoys to torment and kill any creature it thinks it can. They have a hybrid body of a stag and hyena alongside a head akin to a badger which has bodily fluids constantly ooze from its mouth.

Name: Lex Luthor (Post-Crisis)
Summary: Lex Luthor, since his first appearance, has been the most consistent adversary of Superman. His origins have varied somewhat, from the son of an abusive household to the childhood friend of a young Clark Kent, but upon reaching the city of Metropolis, he used his genius intellect and scientific knowledge to become a highly corrupt businessman, and eventually the head of his own corporation, secure in his position as one of the most powerful men in the world.

Name: Lillend
Summary: Lillends were feminine celestials native to Ysgard, but present in many other domains including Limbo and Arborea. Oftentimes they directly served the gods, notably including the likes of Selune, Corellon Larethian, Labelas Enoreth, and many other elvish deities. Rarely would a lillend don clothing as it was an alien concept to their celestial natures. They were great lovers of decadence and luxury, and even were afforded the ultimate luxury from the gods- a lillend could choose the hour in which they die.

Name: Lizardfolk
Summary: Lizardfolk are reptilian humanoids native to the world of Toril that tend to dwell in semi-aquatic environments (such as swamplands and coastlines). An exceedingly practical folk, they do not desire riches or knowledge that don't have use in normal day-to-day survival activities. Their people are hardy, and can adapt to most environments- so despite being dominated culturally by the likes of humans, dwarves, and elves, they rarely hold complaint for the lands leftover for their dominions.

Name: Locathah
Summary: One of D&D's aquatic races, the Locathah is a playable race of fish people. They are resilient, adept in using weapons, and possess natural athleticism alongside sharp senses. However they are bound to water, being only able to be above ground for 4 hours before needing to be covered in water as to not suffocate to death.

Name: Logan Walker
Summary: Sergeant Logan Walker is the youngest member of the Ghosts and the only one that does not speak. During the events of Ghosts stories, he's 16 years old. He is then 25 years old during the events of the other missions. Him and the other Ghosts are sent to find and capture Gabriel Rorke. At the end of the mission The Ghost Killer, he is captured by Rorke and is sent to an unknown location where he suffers the same torture Rorke had endured.

Name: Loop
Summary: This profile contains major spoilers for In Stars And Time and START AGAIN: a prologue. It is highly suggested that you complete In Stars and Time before reading this profile.

Name: Lt. Surge
Summary: Lt. Surge "The Lightning American" is the leader of the Vermillion Gym and mainly uses Electric-type Pokémon. He is the third Gym Leader Red and Blue encounter in their adventures through Kanto. Characterized by his bold and brash composure, Lt. Surge is a war vet who served in the mysterious "Kanto War" of some years ago.

Name: Luke Cage (Marvel Cinematic Universe)
Summary: Luke Cage (real name Carl Lucas) is a former policeman from Savannah, Georgia, who was wrongfully convicted into Seagate Prison, where he met and fell in love with therapist Reva Connors. During his time in prison, he underwent an experiment to save his life that ended up giving him superhuman strength and a seemingly unbreakable skin. After he escaped from his prison, he changed his name and moved to New York City, marrying Connors and living there until her death seemingly due to a random bus crash.

Name: Lulu (League of Legends)
Summary: The yordle mage Lulu is known for conjuring dreamlike illusions and fanciful creatures as she roams Runeterra with her fairy companion Pix. Lulu shapes reality on a whim, warping the fabric of the world, and what she views as the constraints of this mundane, physical realm. While others might consider her magic at best unnatural, and at worst dangerous, she believes everyone could use a touch of enchantment.

Name: Lurker
Summary: Appearing like giant mantarays this monsters have a black back and an underside that looks like stone which aids them to hide in tops of caves where they stay still until a prey passes them by, and when it does they lung at themslves at the target, wrapping around them and crushing them to death.

Name: M'Baku (Marvel Cinematic Universe)
Summary: M'Baku is the leader of the Jabari Tribe and a staunch opponent of T'Challa's rule who ends up torn between challenging him for the throne only to help him defend the Wakanda from Erik Killmonger.

Name: M.O.D.O.K.
Summary: The Advanced Idea Mechanics technician George Tarleton was selected as the victim of a cruel experiment aimed at creating a living computer of unprecedented might. However, instead of becoming the subservient tool his creators craved for, the newly-born M.O.D.O.K. rebelled and imposed himself as the new head of the organization. As twisted in the body as in the mind, he committed himself to further A.I.M.'s ideals according to his personal ambitions.

Name: M1 Abrams
Summary: The M1 Abrams is a third-generation main battle tank designed by General Dynamics Land Systems (formerly Chrysler Defense) and named after General Creighton Abrams. Conceived for modern armored ground warfare, it introduced several innovative features, including a multifuel turbine engine, advanced composite armor, a computer fire control system, separate ammunition storage in a blow-out compartment, and NBC protection.

Name: M4 Sherman
Summary: The M4 Sherman, officially “Medium Tank, M4” and named by the British for the American Civil War General William Tecumseh Sherman, was the most widely used medium tank by the United States and Western Allies in World War II. It is one of the few really iconic fighting vehicles of the Allies during World War Two. The M4 Sherman proved to be reliable, relatively cheap to produce, and available in great numbers. Thousands were distributed through the Lend-Lease program to the British Commonwealth and Soviet Union.

Name: Magma Mephit
Summary: Befitting their name, the Magma Mephit are made from lava, with them using their natural body heat in combat.

Name: Magmin
Summary: Magmin are small fiery elementals that are often summoned by cults of elemental flame. The sole reason these creatures do not explode into fire the second they enter the Material Plane is due to their magma shells which contain their flame. They are chaotic pyromaniacs, who view all that is flammable as kindling for a grand flame to be birthed from. Despite this they are not actively evil, and instead simply do not understand the threat their flames pose to mortals.

Name: Magneto (Marvel Comics)
Summary: Max Eisenhardt, better known as Magneto, is one of the most powerful mutants in the world and a recurring foe of the X-Men. After suffering from multiple tragedies throughout his life, he became determined to end humanity's oppression of mutants by upending the human-led governments of the world.

Name: Mammoth (Dungeons and Dragons)
Summary: An ancient ancestor of the modern day elephant , the Mammoth is massive herbivore from the ice age. Mammoths live in cold plains in in big herds, where their general size makes so besides humanoids nobody bothers trying to hunt them.

Name: Mandarin (Marvel Cinematic Universe)
Summary: Xu Wenwu (Chinese: 文武), better known as The Mandarin, is a major antagonist in the Marvel Cinematic Universe, mostly serving as the unseen overarching antagonist of the Iron Man trilogy and the Marvel one-shot All Hail The King, and the main antagonist of Shang-Chi and the Legend of the Ten Rings.

Name: Mandarin (Marvel Comics)
Summary: The Mandarin was born the child of Mongolian and British aristocrats, both of whom died shortly after his birth. He was raised by his aunt, who was bitter about not being the inheritor of the family fortune and decided to twist his mind, raising him to be vain and bloodthirsty.

Name: Manticore (Dungeons and Dragons)
Summary: Manticores were savage, man-eating magical beasts not dissimilar from the likes of Griffons and Chimeras, in that it was primarily a combination of three other creatures- a lion, a dragon, and a human. Its tail was from some unknown creature or possibly none at all, though it was an extremely deadly tool as it could rapidly fire out spikes as large as a sword.

Name: Me 262 Schwalbe
Summary: The Me 262, nicknamed "Schwalbe" (Swallow), is a twin engine turbojet fighter and the world's first operational jet fighter aircraft. The aircraft made its very first flight on April 18, 1941 with piston engines, making it's maiden flight with jet engines on July 18, one year later. However, it's entrance into Luftwaffe service into the war would be delayed, only being introduced into service in April 1944.

Name: Medusa (Dungeons and Dragons)
Summary: Medusas are creations of powerful Demon Lords or Archdevils, mortals who begged to become beautiful, to become loved. In return, after years of status and acting as a demigod among mortals, they are reduced to medusas, horrifying to behold. They live forever, secluded, turning any who might see them to stone.

Name: Meepo
Summary: Meepo the Dragon-Keeper was once the lowliest of kobolds, weak even for their lowly kind. As such, he was assigned by his then-master, Yusdrayl, to tend to the dragon their tribe had captured, who went by the name of Calcryx; this essentially meant Meepo was assigned to clean the dragon's feces. However, when the dragon was captured by the goblins who also lived in the same dungeon space (dubbed the Sunless Citadel), Meepo's reputation amongst his kin plummeted even lower, and he was destitute, until a party of adventurers arrived and assisted Meepo's tribe in re-capturing the dragon. This state of affairs lasted only briefly before the adventurers ultimately slew the dragon, killing all of Meepo's tribe as a consequence: only Meepo escaped.

Name: Megaloceros (Dungeons and Dragons)
Summary: The Megaloceros which is also known as the Irish Deer is a prehistoric variant of the deer which lived in cold marshes. This animal's antlers could grow up to 10 feet in length and they used said antlers to impale who ever they fought, and while most of the years they're not aggressive during mating season they can be quite dangerous.

Name: Megasaurus
Summary: Megasaurus is a giant fire breathing, car crushing dinosaur robot modeled after a Tyrannosaurus rex (Real World), with hydraulically activated arms, grasping claws, and jaws, as well as flame throwers set up in the head to give the effect of breathing fire from the mouth. It performs across the United States at Monster Jam Truck Shows and other events. Another, almost exact version exists, known as Transaurus.

Name: Merfolk (Dungeons and Dragons)
Summary: Merfolk are humanoid creatures bound to the sea and were half-human, half-fish, created in such a manner by the god Eadro (also known as the Deliverer, the Bather of Gills, and the Lord of the Sunlit Shallows). Aesthetically, they bore more similarities with fey-like creatures such as elves or eladrin than with humans. As with most humanoids they are neutral and can choose their own alignments based on taste. The primary historical threats to their people are merrow (murderous aquatic humanoids), and the consistent Seros wars, terrible conflicts that often decimate the entirety of their population.

Name: Merrow
Summary: Merrow are abyssal aquatic creatures created from fiendishly altered Merfolk. They are spawns of Demogorgon, and serve him as underwater bullies intent on murdering other more wholesome sea-life for the pure sake of chaos. The territory of merrow can generally be identified by their habit of tying corpses to kelp at the boundaries of their underwater dominions. Originally, the merrow were created when a tribe of merfolk opened a portal into the Abyss after a blood sacrifice. Over several generations they transformed into the insane abominations they are now.

Name: Messerschmitt Bf 109
Summary: The Messerschmitt Bf 109 G-6/R3 is a single-engined, single-seat monoplane fighter and a German World War II fighter aircraft that was the backbone of the Luftwaffe's fighter force. The Bf 109 first saw operational service in 1937 during the Spanish Civil War and was still in service at the dawn of the jet age at the end of World War II in 1945. It was one of the most advanced fighters of the era, including such features as all-metal monocoque construction, a closed canopy, and retractable landing gear. It was powered by a liquid-cooled, inverted-V12 aero engine. From the end of 1941, the Bf 109 was steadily being supplemented by the Focke-Wulf Fw 190. It was commonly called the Me 109, most often by Allied aircrew and among the German aces, even though this was not the official German designation.

Name: Mezzoloth
Summary: Mezzoloths serve as the foot soldiers of the Yugoloth armies and thus make up the brunt of their society. Mezzoloths swarm the planar battlefields by the million, hordes of insectoid soldiers goaded forward by their superiors- be they yagnaloths, nycaloths, or ultroloths, the fate remains the same for mezzoloths.

Name: Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-21
Summary: The Mikoyan-Gurevich MiG-21 (Russian: Микоян и Гуревич МиГ-21; NATO reporting name: Fishbed) is a supersonic jet fighter and interceptor aircraft, designed by the Mikoyan-Gurevich Design Bureau in the Soviet Union.

Name: Mil Mi-24
Summary: The Mil Mi-24 is a multipurpose helicopter gunship, which doubles as a low capacity troop transport capable of carrying 8 passengers. It is developed by the Mil Moscow Helicopter Plant of the USSR, making it's first flight on September 19, 1969, entering service for the Red Army in 1972. Since then it has been operated by over 30 other nations.

Name: Milotic
Summary: Feebas is a shabby, old-looking fish-like Pokémon. It has large, hollow eyes, large spots covering its body, dull pink lips and a deprived look. Due to its ugly appearance, it is largely ignored by predators, Trainers, and researchers alike. Despite this however, Feebas has the unique trait of being able to survive in any water, no matter how polluted, making it quite hardy.

Name: Mimic (Dungeons and Dragons)
Summary: Mimics are shapechanging monstrosities typically found in dungeons, posing as lost treasure to lure in unwary creatures for consumption. While they can theoretically become anything of an appropriate size, they are most often depicted as taking the form of chests, imitating a treasure hoard while they await their prey. Rare breeds of mimics can even become humanoid in form, leading to a much more mobile lifestyle. Other variants of mimics exist as well, including "Killer" mimics, which are more lethal than their brethren.

Name: Mind Flayer (Dungeons and Dragons)
Summary: Mind Flayers are horrific, eldritch creatures associated with the dark depths of the D&D settings. They are renowned for being horrendously evil and for their mental capacities. Mind Flayers thrive by devouring the minds of other creatures, generally only interacting with other species at all to eat them or to enslave their kind.

Name: Minotaur (Dungeons and Dragons)
Summary: Minotaurs are cursed individuals, members of a race created by Baphomet, the Horned King, a demon lord that rules an infinite maze in the Abyss. They are massive humanoids with the features of bulls. Previously all minotaurs were male, though this seems to have changed of late now that many minotaurs are breaking free of the curse placed upon them by Baphomet. The most striking thing about these creatures is that, while not particularly intelligent, they are extremely clever in regards to tracking, and it is considered impossible to get them lost.

Name: Mirabelle
Summary: Mirabelle Prunille Pois Chevalier is a major character in the game In Stars and Time and START AGAIN: a prologue, traveling with Isabeau, Odile, Siffrin, and Bonnie on a quest to defeat the King and save Vaugarde from the fate of being frozen in time. She is a kind yet anxious Housemaiden of Change, with the Change belief being a religion practiced in most of Vaugarde whose ideals are about change in both its practitioners and in the world as a whole.

Name: Modron
Summary: Quote? You desire a quote? The One and the Prime does not give 'quotes'.

Name: Moff Gideon
Summary: Moff Gideon was an officer of the Imperial Security Bureau who contributed to the Great Purge against the Mandalorians until graduating to the rank of marshal and then Moff. After the Galactic Empire's downfall, he evaded execution for war crimes and became the leader of a powerful imperial fragment army while seeking a force-sensitive baby of the same species as Jedi master Yoda, causing him and his forces to conflict with The Mandalorian and his allies.

Name: Morgan Le Fay (Marvel Cinematic Universe)
Summary: Morgan le Fay is the main antagonist of the third season of the TV Series Runaways from the Marvel Cinematic Universe. She is a powerful witch trapped in the Dark Dimension who had sought to take control over Nico Minoru and the Staff of One in order to conquer the world. She managed to escape from the Dark Dimension after inciting Minoru to use the correct spell as she initiated a plan to merge the Dark Dimension and Earth, which she then intended to rule over with an army of slaves created through the Corvus WizPhones. To that end, le Fay enthralled Robert Minoru and took over Wizard, and repeatedly tried to have the Staff of One given to her by Nico. However, le Fay's plans for a world domination were finally foiled by an alliance between both the Runaways and PRIDE, and le Fay was then banished back to the Dark Dimension by Tina Minoru.

Name: Mr. Freeze (Post-Crisis)
Summary: Victor Fries was a cryogenics worker operating in Gotham City trying to find a way to cure his ill wife Nora. When he preserved her in cryostasis without authorization from GothCorp, the company tried to shut his research down, and in Victor's attempt to stop them he was caught in a dangerous chemical accident that left him unable to survive outside of very cold temperatures. Building a special suit to keep himself alive, he used it to become the supervillain Mr. Freeze.

Name: Mud Slaad
Summary: Though many believe that the Red Slaad is the weakest of the Slaad kind the one that truly deserves that title is the Mud Slaad. Despite being weaker then the rest of its kin they are still deadly opponents for adventurer parties to face.

Name: Mummy (Dungeons and Dragons)
Summary: Mummies are a type of powerful undead, known primarily for their appearance of ceremonial wrappings around their entire bodies as well as for their horrifying ability to cause creatures to rot away with a single touch. They are typically found in deserts and are raised by the dark gods residing in the sandy dunes. They were normally found guarding tombs containing great wealth, and deterred all but the most resilient adventurers.

Name: Muriel (Hansel & Gretel: Witch Hunters)
Summary: Muriel the Grand Black Witch is the main antagonist of 2013 film Hansel & Gretel: Witch Hunters. She is the leader of the Black Witches, and Hansel and Gretel's arch-nemesis. Powerful, but still vulnerable to fire, she sought an immunity to fire. In order to do so, she needed to sacrifice the heart of a Grand White Witch and twelve children in a ritual sacrifice on the Blood Moon Sabbath.

Name: Muse (Marvel Cinematic Universe)
Summary: Heather Glenn: Bastian, please. Muse: Don't fucking call me that! I am Muse! Muse. M-U-S-E.

Name: Mustard (Pokémon)
Key: '''By Himself''' | '''Pokèmon Team (First battle)''' | '''Pokèmon Team (Second battle)''' | '''Pokèmon Team (Third battle)'''
Summary: Mustard is a character in The Isle of Armor in Pokémon Sword and Shield. He is a former Champion of the Galar region and the mentor of Leon. He is the only character in the games to have the Trainer class Dojo Master.

Name: Myconid
Summary: Myconids are fungal organisms typically found in the Underdark that tend toward a pacifistic bent, and are generally more interested in enlightenment than combat. However, they are known to take up campaigns against the more vile races of the Underdark (such as the drow, duergar, mind flayers, and beholders) if threatened enough. They are known to make use of corpses as servants, infecting them with their spores to make them ambulatory once more. Myconids gather in "circles", small communities typically led by an individual of particular prowess and wisdom known as a sovereign. Myconids in such communities tend to form melds, a sort of group consciousness created via spores telepathically linking each and every member of the community. While in the meld, myconids release hallucinatory spores that grant dream-like visions that carry the primary function of entertainment or socializing, but can and are used to communicate complex ideas or memories.

Name: Mystra (Midnight)
Key: '''Beginning of the Avatar Crisis''' | '''End of the Avatar Crisis''' | '''Avatar''' | '''Greater God'''
Summary: Before she was the God of magic, Mystra was known as the wizard Midnight. Born Ariel Manx, she was the second child of the merchant Theus. A hedonist, Ariel would spend her time with the local bards, sorcerers, fighters, and thieves where she would eventually earn her nickname Midnight due to her late night activities. Eventually she would develop a fascination with magic and left her home in the pursuit of a higher calling.

Name: Nascour
Summary: Nascour (Japanese: ジャキラ Jakira) was thought to be the head of Cipher. A man with a terrifying visage, he is gaunt, dressed in dark clothes and possesses wiry, white, serpentine hair. He is the only character in the games to have the Trainer class Cipher (Japanese: シャドー Shadow). Nascour's strategy in battle is to use X Special and other stat-enhancing items on his Pokémon.

Name: Necrophidius
Summary: A necrophidius appears as a skeletal snake with a fanged human skull for a head. It is generally confused for an undead due to its appearance, but in fact is a construct of fiends used for guards and assassinations. It is a master of infiltration and is capable of remaining still indefinitely to gain access to its target.

Name: Needletooth
Summary: The Needletooth, also known as Needlefang Drake is a small green dinosaur around the size of a cat. It comes in large swarms which fearlessly try to devour any animal they come across, their small size and coloring makes them extremely effective in hiding in dense foliage, jungle, or heavy underbrush areas.

Name: NERDS (Dungeons and Dragons)
Summary: Formed by the Wererat Mr. Honeycomb to solve Harmony city's energy crisis, the NERDS are a group of six adventurers whom each helped the Order of Zimandius to save the city, with them stopping Emo the Beholder from sapping all the color of the world.

Name: Nick Fury (Marvel Cinematic Universe)
Summary: Nick Fury is the former S.H.I.E.L.D. director. He is the spy to beat all spies, keeping tabs as best as he can on all supernatural occurences in the Marvel Cinematic Universe.

Name: Nifern
Summary: The Nifern is a hybrid between a reptile and a dog, with it possessing the shape of a dog but having scales on its body alongside a stinger on its tail, it's also naturally blind due to not having eyes and instead relying on its sense of smell to battle. Due to their reptile qualities they're a popular animal for scalykind like Lizardfolk and their sense of smell also made them a common tracker animal used by creatures such as the Mind Flayers.

Name: Nightmare (Dungeons and Dragons)
Summary: Nightmares are horse-like creatures originating from the Lower Planes, such as the Abyss, the Nine Hells, or Gehenna. They are the standard choice of mount for high-ranking fiends and undead alike, most often searching devil and demon lords, vampires, liches, and other evil-aligned creatures such as the shadar-kai. They are truly wicked beings and are best known for their flaming bodies and vicious tempers.

Name: Nightwing (Post-Crisis)
Summary: Richard John "Dick" Grayson is a fictional superhero that appears in comic books published by DC Comics. Created by Bob Kane and Bill Finger and illustrator Jerry Robinson, he first appeared in Detective Comics #38 in April 1940. The youngest in a family of acrobats known as the "Flying Graysons", Dick watches a mafia boss kill his parents in order to extort money from the circus that employed them.

Name: Nixylanna Vidorant
Summary: Once a member of the Silver Fingers Society Nixylanna Vidorant used to work with Samphith Goldenbeard. However after a robbery where she abandoned him and afterwards refused to share the treasure with him they became bitter rivals. Years later she departs from the Silver Fingers Society while her rival becomes the leader of it, with him soon after sending forces to try and steal from her as revenge and the treasure that he claims is rightfully his.

Name: Nobu (Marvel Cinematic Universe)
Summary: Daredevil: Wait... you're dead! Nobu: There is no such thing.

Name: Nostalgie
Summary: Bourdon is a sadness in the game In Stars and Time, appearing on each floor of Dormont’s House of Change and holding a Star Crest.

Name: Nothic
Summary: Nothics are corrupted spellcasters who peered too deeply into the secrets of their vile masters. Vecna, in ages past, created a creeping curse for secretive mages who sought great power. The more they looked into the foul secrets they researched endlessly, the more likely it would be that they would be transformed into a Nothic. Much of the followers of Acererak fell to such a fate, as did many arcanists of Netherese who weren't fortunate enough to become liches following their civilization's collapse.

Name: Nunu and Willump
Summary: Once upon a time, there was a boy who wanted to prove he was a hero by slaying a fearsome monster—only to discover that the beast, a lonely and magical yeti, merely needed a friend. Bound together by ancient power and a shared love of snowballs, Nunu and Willump now ramble wildly across the Freljord, breathing life into imagined adventures. They hope that somewhere out there, they will find Nunu’s mother. If they can save her, maybe they will be heroes after all…

Name: Oblex
Summary: An Oblex is a collection of sentient slime created by the Illithids through various experiments in the Underdark. Akin to its creators, The Oblex shares a diet for the minds of others and is devoted entirely to absorbing the substance, using its wits to stalk intelligent prey before proceeding to engulf its prey's head, draining out their memories and personality while leaving the prey clueless and perplexed afterward, if not dead. These memories are presumably represented by the head of its victim.

Name: Ochre Jelly
Summary: Old favorites time, is it? I know that ye folks that play at the sort o' things that happen for real in the Realms are overly fond of pitting yer characters against witless giant amoebas! Just about their style, eh? Witless giant amoebas? Ochre jellies, ye dolt!

Name: Odile
Summary: Sachiko Odile Aiuchi is a major character in the game In Stars and Time and START AGAIN: a prologue, traveling with Mirabelle, Isabeau, Siffrin, and Bonnie on a quest to defeat the King and save Vaugarde from the fate of being frozen in time. She is a curious and perceptive traveler from Ka Bue, thought to be a researcher by the rest of her party.

Name: Ogre (Dungeons and Dragons)
Summary: Ogres are a low-ranking species of giants, taking the position of the bottom rung of the Ordning, the social structure of the Giants. Ogres are big, dumb, and strong- perfect units for the foot soldiers of the giant armies.

Name: Okoye (Marvel Cinematic Universe)
Summary: Okoye is the general of Dora Milaje and the head of Wakanda's armed forces and intel.

Name: Olaf
Summary: Most men would say that death is a thing to be feared; none of those men would be Olaf. The Berserker lives only for the roar of a battle cry and the clash of steel. Spurred on by his hunger for glory and the looming curse of a forgettable death, Olaf throws himself into every fight with reckless abandon. Surrendering to the bloodlust deep within his being, Olaf is only truly alive when grappling with the jaws of death.

Name: Oni (Dungeons and Dragons)
Summary: The Mage Ogre commonly known as the Oni is a variant of the Ogre which is far more dangerous due to its innate magical abilities, regeneration, and higher intelligence.

Name: Onomatopoeia (Post-Crisis)
Summary: Named for his verbal tic of verbally repeating sounds of the world around him, the enigmatic Onomatopoeia is a serial killer of the most dangerous game: superheroes. Generally targeting rookie, third-rate non-powered heroes, Onomatopoeia eventually kills his way up to the likes of Green Arrow and even Batman, using his strategic genius and excellent physical condition to hunt and kill whoever he chooses as his latest target.

Name: Oreioth
Summary: Oreioth was a necromancer during the Elemental Evil crisis, and was born into a world of hatred. At a young age he would commit atrocities such as murdering infant children for the sole intent of savoring his power over their death.

Name: Otyugh
Summary: Look out to the base of the wall there... look hard, and look for an enemy. An eye! An eye... coming up from the ground like a worm! But- but- what is it, out there? Only your father can tell you that, Erammon. And if I were you, I'd make sure he was in a good mood when I asked him.

Name: Owlbear
Summary: Owlbears are a chimeric, magical combination of owls and bears (as the name implies), and are known to be terrible predators. They are famed for their ill tempers and ferocity- a fight with an owlbear is a fight to the death. Once they were natives to the Feywild, however they have since migrated to other worlds.

Name: Owlman (Post-Crisis)
Summary: In an antimatter universe, Thomas Wayne and his oldest son, Thomas Jr., survived the murder of the Wayne family, while Bruce was killed. This lead to Thomas Jr. giving himself training, gadgets and artificial intellect enhancements to operate as a prominent criminal, and member of the supervillain Crime Syndicate of Amerika, as Owlman.

Name: Pegasus (Dungeons and Dragons)
Summary: Pegasi are a race of winged equine creatures hailing from the plane of Arborea, and are often considered symbols of peace, goodness, and beauty, and were often used as mounts for the avatars of the Seldarine. Despite sharing some similarities, pegasi despise Griffons and Hippogriffs and will go out of their way to destroy them. However, in general a pegasus would prefer to flee rather than engage in combat.

Name: Peggy Carter (Marvel Cinematic Universe)
Summary: Peggy Carter was a British agent who ended up working for the SSR with Project Rebirth during WW2. She befriended and started a relationship with Captain America, until his crash into the ice.
